<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<!-- When creating a new activity, make a copy of this file with appropriate name -->
<worksheet>
  <title>Final Exam - Math 122</title>

  <!-- Optional introduction -->
  <introduction>
    <p>
      You will solve each of the following problems, making sure to justify them with explanation and supporting computations.  Keep the following in mind.
      <ul>
        <li>
            <p>
                On all problems, you must show all work necessary to justify your solution.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p>
                On all problems, you must find a way to explain your reasoning.  You must do this in complete sentences.
            </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <!-- Exercises start here. -->
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        (34 pts.) For the following problem, note that for a polynomial <m>f(x)</m>, if <m>r</m> is a root of <m>f(x)</m> (i.e. <m>f(r)=0</m>), we say that <m>r</m> has multiplicity <m>k</m> if we can factor out <m>(x-r)^k</m> from <m>f(x)</m>.  So for the polynomial <m>f(x) = 5(x-4)^5(x+6)^3</m>, the root 4 has multiplicity 5 and the root <m>-6</m> has multiplicity 3.
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find a formula for a polynomial that has roots at <m>x=-3</m> and <m>x=5</m>, where both roots have multiplicity 2, and where the <m>y</m>-intercept is at <m>(0,28)</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find the formula for a polynomial that has degree 9, has roots of multiplicity 1 at <m>x=-3</m> and <m>x=5</m>, has roots of multiplicity 2 at <m>x=-2</m> and <m>x=3</m>, and has a root of multiplicity 3 at <m>x=1</m>.  Also, as <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m>, we have <m>f(x) \rightarrow -\infty</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    A polynomial <m>g(x)</m> has its graph given below.  Determine a possible formula for <m>g(x)</m>. Explain why your formula is consistent with the graph below.  In your explanation, explain why your function has the correct end behavior (i.e. what happens when <m>x \rightarrow \infty</m> and when <m>x \rightarrow -\infty</m>); explain why your formula has the correct <m>x</m>-intercepts; and explain why the behavior of the graph at the <m>x</m>-intercepts is consistent between your formula and the graph.
                </p>
                <image width="60%">
                	<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="poly-graph">
                		<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
                			<definition>g(x)=-0.005*(x+3)^3*(x-1)^2*(x-4)</definition>
                			<coordinates bbox="(-5,-5,5,5)">
                    			<grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y"/>
                    			<graph function="g"/>
                    			<point p="(2,g(2))" alignment="se"> <m>(2,1.25)</m> </point>
                  			</coordinates>
                		</diagram>
                	</prefigure>
                </image>
            </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
    <statement>
        <p>
            (27 pts.) A rectangular box is being constructed so that its base is twice as long as it is wide. In addition, the base and top of the box cost $2 per square foot while the sides cost $1.50 per square foot. We only want to spend $10 on materials for the box.  Let <m>w</m> be the width of the base, <m>\ell</m> be the length of the base, and <m>h</m> be the height of the box.
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (3 pts.) What is the volume of the box?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (11 pts.) We know the total cost of the box is $10, but what is the total cost of the box in terms of <m>w</m>, <m>\ell</m>, and <m>h</m>?
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        (13 pts.) Write the volume of the box in terms of one variable.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>